## 2. Core Entities & API Design

### Q: What are the core entities?

| Entity | What it is | Example |
|--------|-----------|---------|
| File | Raw bytes | A 2GB video, a 50KB PDF |
| FileMetadata | Info about the file | name, size, mimeType, uploadedBy, status |
| User | Person using the system | email, userId |

### Q: What do the APIs look like?

| Action | Endpoint | Notes |
|--------|----------|-------|
| Upload | `POST /files/presigned-url` | Returns presigned URL for direct S3 upload |
| Download | `GET /files/{fileId}/presigned-url` | Returns signed CDN URL |
| Share | `POST /files/{fileId}/share` | Body: list of user IDs/emails |
| Sync check | `GET /files/changes?since={timestamp}` | Returns ChangeEvent[] |

User identity comes from headers (JWT or session token) — never the request body, since body can be tampered with.

APIs evolve as you design. Tell the interviewer upfront: "I'll outline simple APIs but may refine them as we go deeper."

