## 8. Performance Optimizations

### Q: What are all the ways to make uploads/downloads faster?

| Technique | Helps with | How |
|-----------|-----------|-----|
| CDN | Downloads | Cache at edge, serve from nearest POP |
| Parallel chunk upload | Uploads | Multiple chunks in flight simultaneously |
| Content-Defined Chunking (CDC) | Sync | Only re-upload chunks that actually changed |
| Compression (Zstandard) | Both | Fewer bytes to transfer |
| Adaptive chunk sizing | Uploads | Bigger chunks on fast networks, smaller on slow |

### Q: What is Content-Defined Chunking and why does it matter?

With fixed-size chunks (every 5MB), inserting ONE byte at the start shifts ALL chunk boundaries. Every chunk fingerprint changes. You'd re-upload the entire file for a 1-byte edit.

**CDC** uses a rolling hash (Rabin fingerprinting) to determine chunk boundaries based on content. Insert a byte? Only 1-2 surrounding chunks change. The other 99 chunks keep their fingerprints.

This is how real Dropbox achieves efficient delta sync.

### Q: When should you compress files?

| File type | Compress? | Why |
|-----------|-----------|-----|
| Text files, logs, CSVs | Yes | 5GB → 500MB possible |
| Images (PNG, JPEG) | No | Already compressed, <2% savings |
| Videos (MP4) | No | Already compressed |
| Archives (ZIP) | No | Already compressed |

Algorithm comparison:
- **Gzip**: Most widely supported, moderate speed/ratio
- **Brotli**: Better ratio than Gzip for text, supported by all modern browsers
- **Zstandard**: Best balance of speed + ratio, tunable, ideal for client-side work

Rule: Always compress BEFORE encrypting (encryption adds randomness that makes compression useless).

