## Interview-Ready One-Liners

### "Why use presigned URLs instead of uploading through your server?"
> "The server should be a traffic cop, not a cargo truck. Presigned URLs let the client upload directly to S3 — the server just generates a signed permission slip using local crypto, never touching the file bytes. This eliminates double bandwidth cost and prevents the server from being a bottleneck."

### "How do you handle a 50GB upload?"
> "Chunked multipart upload. Client splits into 5-10MB chunks, uploads each directly to S3 via individual presigned URLs (in parallel), and the backend tracks chunk status for resumability. S3's CompleteMultipartUpload assembles the final object."

### "Why don't downloads need chunking?"
> "Once multipart upload completes, S3 stores a single assembled object. Downloads use one signed URL plus HTTP Range requests for resumability — it's built into the protocol, no custom chunking needed."

### "How do you keep files in sync across devices?"
> "Hybrid approach: WebSocket pushes real-time change events, plus periodic polling as a safety net to catch anything missed during connection drops."

### "Why availability over consistency for Dropbox?"
> "Nobody loses money or has a safety issue if a file takes 3 seconds to appear on another device. Availability matters more — users should always be able to upload and access their files."

